reviews.review_text:
Those were good days!  We lived in the Fan District in Richmond in those days and my dad had this Victorian House with a carriage house out back. My brother, who graduate from VPI at Virginia Tech in 1982, invited all his friends to crash after the show. They started to trickle in, after the show, with tales of their quest after the show in finding the correct bus. Of course they were all spun out of their gorde but, It was pretty funny to listen to them describe the experience. I recall those shows a melee, Richmond had just completed the 6th Street Market Place, adjacent to the coliseum and were desperate to realize a ROI in the 6th St. Market, yet welcomed visitors by pulling them out of cars and arresting them. The police lock up is right across the street and "Just Say No" was being heavily promoted. Of course our motto was " just say mo" One of my brothers friends got busted and I tried to use his ticket to get in the next night.........didn't work but, I found one eventually. I think the GD management said "we will play Richmond again when they tear down the police station"

I last time I saw Jerry Garcia RIP perform was at the Richmond Coliseum 12 years later where he sang The Day They Tore Old Dixie Down.

One thing, about the 1985 shows I will never forget was when Phil hit the resonance frequency of the coliseum, on one night, and the place shook so hard I thought the walls would cave in for a second or two. The whole place was oscillating.
